The omission of conjunctions (asyndeton) is frequent, owing to Tacitus⁷ rhetorical tendencies ; in lively narration: amplecti adlevare adhortari, xii 51, 3 ; in enumerations, often leading up to a climax: tempus preces satias, vi 38, 1 ; omnis sexus, omnis aetas, inlustres ignobiles, vi 19, 3; decus pudorem corpus cuncta regno viliora habere, xii 65, 4.

49 [66]. Adverbs are used as adjectives, attributively, as in Greek: nullis extrinsecus adiumentis, xii 61, 4; and even predicatively: multis coram, vi 42, 6 ; nullis palam . . . causis, xi 22, 1.

50 [67]. Tamquam, quasi, and (less frequently) velut are used—

(a) of something pretended or alleged to be the reason for the fact described: finem accepit quasi nescius exercendi, vi 11, 53 is velut propria ad negotia digrediens . . .‚ vi 50, 4 ; in exilium agitur quasi finem principis per Chaldaeos scrutaretur, xii 52, 1 3 gloriam adeptos tamquam reppererint, xi 14, 1 ;
